{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17630568","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17630568"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:17:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:17:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17318"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17318","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17318"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10008"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69870"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10008","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10008"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17318"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55326"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"6930"},{"type":"tags","id":"10043"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23448"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23456"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69870","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69870"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of haustral contractions in the large intestine?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Create high-pressure contractions","Stimulate water secretion","Promote rapid transit of contents","Generate rapid peristaltic waves","Mix and slowly propel colonic contents"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMixing and slow propulsion of colonic contents\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary function of haustral contractions. These gentle, segmental contractions occur approximately three times per hour and help to expose colonic contents to the mucosal surface for water absorption while gradually moving material towards the rectum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenerating rapid peristaltic waves\u003C/strong\u003E - Rapid peristalsis is not a feature of haustral contractions; these are characteristic of mass movements which occur only 2-3 times daily\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulating water secretion\u003C/strong\u003E - The colon primarily absorbs rather than secretes water; haustral contractions aid this absorption process\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPromoting rapid transit of contents\u003C/strong\u003E - Haustral contractions are associated with slow transit, taking approximately 12-24 hours for contents to traverse the colon\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECreating high-pressure contractions\u003C/strong\u003E - Haustral contractions are low-amplitude, gentle movements rather than forceful contractions\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaustral contractions are essential for normal colonic function, allowing sufficient time for water absorption and the formation of solid faeces.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The primary function of haustral contractions in the large intestine is to mix and slowly propel colonic contents.","Haustral contractions occur approximately three times per hour and are responsible for mechanical digestion in the colon.","Mass movements in the colon are distinct from haustral contractions and occur only a few times per day."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55326"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17318"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55326"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-12T21:16:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-12T21:17:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10008"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69870"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":nu